99add7ce-8d9e-966f-4cdb-7e8d78c95499.title	"Mars needs rovers! (and it just got a big one)"
99add7ce-8d9e-966f-4cdb-7e8d78c95499.author	"Matthew Francis"
99add7ce-8d9e-966f-4cdb-7e8d78c95499.categories	["Features","Scientific Method","astronomy","Mars","Mars Curiosity","Mars Phoenix lander","Mars rovers","planetary science","Viking landers"]
99add7ce-8d9e-966f-4cdb-7e8d78c95499.date	"2012-08-05T20:30:49.000Z"
99add7ce-8d9e-966f-4cdb-7e8d78c95499.description	"<div class=\"intro-image image center full-width\" style=\"width:640px\">\n      <img src=\"http://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2012/07/Opportunity_panorama_Greeley_crater-640x220.jpg\" width=\"640\" height=\"220\">\n  \n  </div>\n <p>Where else can you find another world like Earth? Venus is similar in size and mass to our planet, but its broiling hot surface temperature and sulfuric acid rain put some hard limits on comparisons; other interesting worlds lack atmospheres or are frozen over. But Mars has potential. Despite the thin carbon dioxide atmosphere and low surface gravity (if you weigh 150 pounds on Earth, you'd only weigh 56 pounds on Mars), the planet is just enough like Earth to offer the promise of habitability—whether in the future by humans, or in the past or present by native life forms.</p>\n<p>So it's no surprise that Mars was an exploration target from the very beginning of spaceflight. The first missions sent to Mars by the Soviet Union began in 1960, a scant three years after Sputnik. The first successful flyby came in 1965 with NASA's Mariner 4, and the first successful landing was the Soviet Mars 3 in 1971. That lander ceased transmission soon after touchdown, which is common on the Red Planet—Wikipedia's <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Exploration_of_Mars#Timeline\">timeline of Mars exploration</a> is a sobering read for that very reason.</p>\n<p>The many failures make the successful landings look even more amazing. With the Mars Science Laboratory (MSL) rover, known as Curiosity, arriving on-planet August 6, we're going to take a look back at the landers and rovers that brought us to today.</p><p><a href=\"http://arstechnica.com/science/2012/08/mars-needs-rovers-and-its-getting-a-big-one/\">Read 26 remaining paragraphs</a> | <a href=\"http://arstechnica.com/science/2012/08/mars-needs-rovers-and-its-getting-a-big-one/?comments=1#comments-bar\">Comments</a></p>\n<p><a href=\"http://feedads.g.doubleclick.net/~at/7If4mo7pHL6NUwUJCl060HfIlag/0/da\"><img src=\"http://feedads.g.doubleclick.net/~at/7If4mo7pHL6NUwUJCl060HfIlag/0/di\" border=\"0\" ismap=\"true\"></img></a><br/>\n<a href=\"http://feedads.g.doubleclick.net/~at/7If4mo7pHL6NUwUJCl060HfIlag/1/da\"><img src=\"http://feedads.g.doubleclick.net/~at/7If4mo7pHL6NUwUJCl060HfIlag/1/di\" border=\"0\" ismap=\"true\"></img></a></p><img src=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~r/arstechnica/features/~4/RgP-rDJvKi0\" height=\"1\" width=\"1\"/>"
